gen s08_side_by_side 10 'A single procession of real living animals walks steadily left to right along one dirt trail through golden savanna, and every stage of the procession is a COUPLE walking SHOULDER TO SHOULDER, side by side, keeping pace: two frogs, then two lizards, then two meerkat-like mammals, then — at the front, closest to camera — two monkeys. In every couple one animal is warm coral-orange and the other cool teal-blue, and both animals of a couple are the SAME SPECIES. Every animal walks the SAME WAY, left to right, in profile; no animal ever turns to face another, and nobody walks toward anybody. As they travel, one of the monkeys turns its head to glance sideways at its partner beside it, checking she is keeping up, and then faces forward again. The camera tracks smoothly alongside them, holding the procession in frame. Every animal is a real photographed animal — never knitted, felt, plush or cartoon. No aquariums, no tanks, no carts, no man-made objects. Throughout, one of the pair is warm coral-orange and the other is cool teal-blue — this colour pairing never swaps and never changes. Nobody speaks and nobody sings. No lips move. There is no dialogue, no narrator and no voiceover in this clip. Photorealistic, natural human motion, no slow motion, no speed ramping, no text, no captions, no subtitles, no watermark, no on-screen graphics. Every character keeps exactly the same face, hair and clothes as in the start image and the reference images. Warm 35mm film look, soft golden practical light, gentle grain.' --start-image $F/s08_side_by_side.png --image $A/pair_fish.png --image $A/pair_monkeys.png
gen s35_dioramas 8 'Slow continuous lateral dolly down a corridor of glowing natural-history diorama cases in a dark empty museum. Inside the cases, lit warmly and perfectly still: two lobe-finned fish with their snouts nudged together; two early primates hanging upside-down holding hands, foreheads bonked; two shaggy fur-covered early hominids (primate animals with thick body hair, one rust-orange furred and one blue-grey furred) standing forehead to forehead in tall grass — EXACTLY the pairs from the reference images. EVERY case in the corridor without exception holds a COUPLE — two animals of the same species, one warm coral-orange and one cool teal-blue, posed touching. Not one case holds a lone animal or a plain drab-coloured animal. Every diorama is a PAIR, frozen mid-affection, as if watching. The animals in the cases never move. Walking past them down the corridor, small in frame, are a warm, funny woman of about thirty-two with dark curly shoulder-length hair, freckles, laugh lines and an enormous uncontrollable grin, wearing a soft coral-orange knitted cardigan over a cream t-shirt, faded jeans, and bare feet, a tall soft-featured gentle man of about thirty-four with messy light-brown hair, round wire glasses, a slightly startled kind face and stubble, wearing a rumpled teal-blue button-down shirt with the sleeves rolled up and grey jeans and their daughter, and NOBODY ELSE — no other visitors, no staff, no other family. The creatures in the cases do not move. Nobody speaks and nobody sings. No lips move. There is no dialogue, no narrator and no voiceover in this clip. Photorealistic, natural human motion, no slow motion, no speed ramping, no text, no captions, no subtitles, no watermark, no on-screen graphics. Every character keeps exactly the same face, hair and clothes as in the start image and the reference images. Warm 35mm film look, soft golden practical light, gentle grain.' --start-image $F/s35_dioramas.png --image $A/pair_fish.png --image $A/pair_monkeys.png --image $A/pair_hominids.png --image $A/may.png --image $A/ollie.png --image $A/kid.png --image $A/loc_museum.png
